At all times relevant to this Complaint, Exchange A charged a take fee of
50 cents per contract and, at the highest volume tier, paid a make rebate
of 53 cents per contract. Exchange A paid the 3 cents difference itself to
incentivize liquidity on the exchange.

An options contract is generally for 100 shares. So you can make about half
a penny per share by providing liquidity in this contract.

These fees are generally paid to brokerage firms that send the orders to
the exchange. Some brokerage firms pass them on to customers: If you send a
liquidity-creating order, the brokerage gets 53 cents and passes most of it
to you (for instance it gives you 43 cents and keeps 10); if you send a
liquidity-taking order, the broker pays 50 cents and charges you for it.
Other brokerages do not; they keep the make fees for themselves and pay the
take fees themselves.

One thing you could do is trade options back and forth with yourself using
